If the matrix $$A = \left( {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 2  \cr 
   K &amp; { - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right)$$ satisfies $$A({A^3} + 3I) = 2I$$, then the value of K is :

solution:
Given matrix $$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 2  \cr 
   k &amp; { - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$${A^4} + 3IA = 2I$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {A^4} = 2I - 3A$$<br><br>Also characteristic equation of A is $$|A - \lambda I|\, = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   {0 - \lambda } &amp; 2  \cr 
   k &amp; { - 1 - \lambda }  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \lambda  + {\lambda ^2} - 2k = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow A + {A^2} = 2K.I$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {A^2} = 2KI - A$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {A^4} = 4{K^2}I + {A^2} - 4AK$$<br><br>Put $${A^2} = 2KI - A$$<br><br>and $${A^4} = 2I - 3A$$<br><br>$$2I - 3A = 4{K^2}I + 2KI - A - 4AK$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow I(2 - 2K - 4{K^2}) = A(2 - 4K)$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow  - 2I(2{K^2} + K - 1) = 2A(1 - 2K)$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow  - 2I(2K - 1)(K + 1) = 2A(1 - 2K)$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow (2K - 1)(2A) - 2I(2K - 1)(K + 1) = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow (2K - 1)[2A - 2I(K + 1)] = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow K = {1 \over 2}$$

